In real enterprise data centers, backend servers (workers and databases) almost never have their own direct connection to the internet. Instead, they stay in a private "subnet" and use a Gateway or Proxy to reach the outside world. Setting this up manually shows you understand:

    Network Routing: How data packets move between different subnets. 🛣️

    IP Forwarding: Turning a Linux server into a functional router. 🚦

    Security Architecture: Keeping sensitive data (like your MySQL facts) completely invisible to the public. 🔒
- mysql doesn't have a manually created systemd like nodejs since installing mysql and enabling it creates a mysql process automatically ran by systemd that runs 24/7
- no reverse proxy added in sites-available nginx configs for mysql port and process since the database exists in the same vm server as the api and the website
- no need to open a mysql port through firewall since they're are on the same server, the api talks to mysql through its port locally (localhost), which is secure from the public
- architecture picture with load balancing
- Centralized DB: Both Worker 1 and Worker 2 connect to a single, dedicated Database VM (VM3). This ensures "Data Integrity"—no matter which worker a user hits, they see the same facts. If a user adds a new "Fact" while connected to any of the Workers, that fact won't exist on all other Workers. The data becomes consistent. A single source of truth
- add; project was built with security and scalability first and in high consideration

- learn "Here Document" (the EOF syntax) and tee command

-----------------------architecture(vms and internal network)------------------------------
🌐 The Edge Layer: VM1 (Load Balancer & Gateway)

VM1 acts as the "Front Door" and the "Border Controller." * Public Side: It is the only machine visible to the outside world via its Bridged adapter.

    Private Side: It manages the LAN Segment, providing a secure environment for the other servers.

    The Logic: We enabled IP Forwarding to allow traffic to pass between these two worlds. Because your internal VMs (VM2-4) have private IPs that the public internet doesn't recognize, we used IP Masquerading (NAT). This "masks" the workers' requests with VM1's public IP so they can download updates without being directly exposed to hackers. 🎭

🏗️ The Application Layer: VM2 & VM3 (Workers)

These are your "Engine Rooms."

    They are completely isolated from the internet for security.

    They use VM1 as their Default Gateway to reach the outside world.

    In the next phase, VM1 will use Port Forwarding (Reverse Proxying) to "hand off" incoming web traffic to these workers, balancing the load between them. ⚖️

💾 The Data Layer: VM4 (Database)

This is the "Vault."

    It sits at the deepest level of your network.

    By placing it here, you ensure that even if a worker is compromised, the database remains hidden from direct public access. 🔒
